prompt:
Our calibration benches are driven by a little supervisor process: the in-process layer never touches hardware directly, it appends action lines to a journal (just a vector of strings) and the bench daemon replays them. Right now every code path hand-writes its own "append open, remember to append close" bookkeeping and we keep leaking closes on early returns. I want proper RAII guards for this, C++20, stdlib only. Two new files: guard.hpp and guard.cpp.

The header must provide exactly this surface:

    using ActionLog = std::vector<std::string>;

    class FileGuard {
    public:
        FileGuard() noexcept;                         // inactive, journals nothing ever
        FileGuard(ActionLog& log, std::string path);  // appends "open <path>" now
        ~FileGuard();                                 // appends "close <path>" if still active
        FileGuard(FileGuard&&) noexcept;
        FileGuard& operator=(FileGuard&&) noexcept;
        FileGuard(const FileGuard&) = delete;         // copying a handle makes no sense
        FileGuard& operator=(const FileGuard&) = delete;
        bool active() const noexcept;
        const std::string& path() const noexcept;     // "" when inactive
        void release();                                // close early; safe to call again
    };

    class LockGuard;        // identical shape: "lock <name>" / "unlock <name>",
                            // accessor is name() instead of path()

    class StationSession {  // one bench run = hold the station lock, keep the file open
    public:
        StationSession(ActionLog& log, const std::string& station, const std::string& file);
        // move-only like the guards; copying deleted
        bool active() const noexcept;
        const std::string& station() const noexcept;  // "" when inactive
        const std::string& file() const noexcept;     // "" when inactive
        void release();
    };

Semantics, spelled out because this is exactly where our hand-rolled version went wrong:

- Journal lines are exactly "open <path>", "close <path>", "lock <name>", "unlock <name>" — one line per real acquisition or release, nothing else. Moving a guard around must not journal anything.
- Destruction releases if (and only if) the guard is still active. Scope exit therefore releases in reverse declaration order — the daemon depends on that.
- Move construction transfers ownership: source goes inactive (empty path, no close from it, ever).
- Move assignment first releases whatever the target currently holds (that close line lands at assignment time, before anything else), then adopts the source's resource. Assigning from an inactive guard just releases the target. Self-move must be a harmless no-op — it happens in our std::swap-heavy sort code.
- release() journals the close/unlock immediately, flips the guard inactive (path()/name() become ""), and further release() calls or destruction do nothing.
- Guards must be safely storable in a std::vector — reallocation moves them; every resource still gets exactly one close.
- StationSession composes the two: construction journals "lock <station>" then "open <file>"; release/destruction journals "close <file>" then "unlock <station>" — the file must never outlive the lock. Move-only as well; release() idempotent.
- No globals, no statics: several logs may be live at once and must not interfere.

Worked example, one scope:

    ActionLog log;
    {
        LockGuard l(log, "bench-4");
        FileGuard f(log, "bench-4/run.bin");
    }
    // log == {"lock bench-4", "open bench-4/run.bin",
    //         "close bench-4/run.bin", "unlock bench-4"}

`make test` is the acceptance gate; Makefile, mintest.h and test_guard.cpp are fixed.
